Name: Azlan Hashim
Title: Hello Tripoli!!
Description:
Tripoli, the northern city of Lebanon takes about 1 hour drive by road. It's the 2nd largest city in Lebanon after Beirut. I love Tripoli because of the extreme friendliness of the people here and the atmosphere of this place which is very authentic.  The landmark for the centre of the city is the clock tower  facing the main square where most public transport located.

Name: KoRaYeM
Title: "I don't think so" (Maher Zain)
Description:
ALL RIGHTS RESERVED. PLEASE DONT COPY OR USE THIS PHOTO WITHOUT PERMISSION
______________________________________________________________

I was lucky enough to be invited by @AnasTolba to photoshoot Maher Zain.

Zain is a Swedish singer from Lebanese origins. His song "Ya Nabi Salam Alayka" won the best religious song in a survey in 2009 on "3alahwa" with Ahmed Younis on Cairo's biggest radio station "Nogoum FM"!

His album "Thank you Allah" is pop styled album with tons of tracks with great melodies. The album is produced by Awakening, the same production company that produces the albums of "Sami Yusuf" and "Hamza Namira".

It was a great photoshoot. I was a bit worried to take this "burden" of shooting an artist who thrives to represent muslims in a moderate way since I will have to take photos that extend such imagery through photography. Bas Alhamdolillah, after doing istikhara, I confirmed "I will do it". After all it was a great opportunity for me to meet Maher in person as I love his work.

I post-processed all photos in Lightroom while listening to Maher's beautiful voice to make sure "I am in the mood" :)

Hope you enjoy the photos....

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Maher Zain Biography:
_________________________
Maher’s first musical inspiration came from his father, who was a singer himself, performing locally in the beautiful Mediterranean city of Tripoli - Lebanon.
Fascinated by the music and instruments, Maher got his first keyboard when he was only ten and ever since music officially became part of Maher’s world.

The family moved to Sweden when Maher was only 8, where he continued his schooling, and later entered university and got a Bachelors degree in Aeronautical Engineering. With things changing around him, one thing remained the same - his strong passion for music. He would spend late nights at school with his friends where they would sing, rap, compose and experiment with music in every way. It didn’t take him long to realize that music became an integral part of who he is.

After being involved for a while in the music scene in Sweden as a music producer, Maher was introduced to RedOne, a gifted music producer who was fast rising in the music scene in Sweden. Maher started working with RedOne with Swedish artists, and later moved with him to New York. For a few years he was in the middle of the hot rush of the NY music industry, working with chart topping artists such as Kat Deluna on her debut album which included smash hits ‘Whine up’ and ‘Run the Show’.
Maher had what many would describe as a dream job for someone so young in such a glamorous business, but for Maher it felt like this was far from what he would call ‘the dream’, “I loved the music but I hated everything that surrounded it, it always felt like something wasn’t right”. RedOne was on the verge of breaking into the big time, going on to work with artists like Akon, Lady Gaga, Enrique Iglesias, Brandy, New Kids on the Block, and Michael Jackson to mention just a few, and becoming one of the most sought-after music producers in the world. Maher however was restless and eventually decided that the music industry and all that surrounded wasn’t the right place for him and he returned to Sweden. It wasn’t until he met a group of brothers who were active in the Islamic community in Stockholm and he started regularly attending his local mosque that he felt like he’d reached ‘home’.

Maher feels blessed to able to finally find the right way, and feels like it’s his turn now to help others through his music to do the same: “If I had one thing I’d like to tell people out there it would be that it’s so easy to see the right way if we just open our eyes and look properly; that’s what happened to me.”
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Name: Alessandra Kocman
Title: Inside the Krak des Chevaliers
Description:
Krak des Chevaliers is a Crusader fortress in Syria and one of the most important preserved medieval military castles in the world. In Arabic, the fortress is called Qal'at al-Ḥiṣn (Arabic: قلعة الحصن‎). It is located approximately 40 km west of the city of Homs, close to the border of Lebanon, and is administratively part of the Homs Governorate.

The castle was made a World Heritage Site, along with Qal’at Salah El-Din, in 2006, and is owned by the Syrian government. The fortress is one of the few sites where Crusader art (in the form of frescoes) has been preserved.

The castle is located east of Tripoli, Lebanon, in the Homs Gap, atop a 650-metre-high hill along the only route from Antioch to Beirut and the Mediterranean Sea. It is one of many fortresses that were part of a defensive network along the border of the old Crusader states. The fortress controlled the road to the Mediterranean, and from this base, the Hospitallers could exert some influence over Lake Homs to the east to control the fishing industry and watch for Muslim armies gathering in Syria.

The original fortress at this location had been built in 1031 for the emir of Aleppo.

Name: robertschrader
Title: Curiosity, Killing and Cats
Description:
Martyr's Square, September 2010

"This isn't to say that certain aspects of daily life in Beirut don't call to mind a war zone -- or more of a war zone than I'd previously encountered, anyway. Armed guards are a common site in the Lebanese capital, especially in heavy-traffic areas like Martyr's Square and the Beyrouth Souks shopping complex, picture above. The soliders who man these checkpoints, however, aren't bloodthirsty meatheads who haplessly kill any passer by who approaches them -- this cat's curiosity sure didn't kill him. The strapping gentleman packing this weaponry took a few minutes not only to greet the pint-sized spectator, but also to flirt with his apparently single mother."

In ancient times, Tripoli was the center of a Phoenician confederation which included Tyre, Sidon and Arados, hence the name Tripoli, meaning "triple city" in Greek. Name: JAIRO BD
Title: You Abud? Me Abud!
Description:
In 1926, with two small children and pregnant with my father, my grandmother decided to leave Lebanon and journey to Brazil, in the hopes of leading here a more peaceful and prosperous life. She died 29 years ago and the small family she brought up here gradually lost contact with any relatives who still lived there. I just knew she was born in a small northern village, a few kilometers away from Tripoli. Last week, while talking to a few restaurant employees in Tripoli, one of them asked my full name. To mine and everybody else’s surprise, he exclaimed: “You Abud? Me Abud!”

Let me introduce you to Abdel Majid Abud, my long lost cousin… :)

Em 1926, com dois filhos pequenos e grávida do meu pai, minha avó decidiu deixar o Líbano e viajar ao Brasil, na esperança de uma vida mais pacífica e próspera. Ela morreu 29 anos atrás, e a pequena família que trouxe até aqui foi perdendo contato com parentes que ainda vivem por lá. Eu só sabia que ela nasceu em uma pequena vila do norte, a poucos quilómetros de Tripoli. Na semana passada, enquanto conversávamos com alguns funcionários de um restaurante em Trípoli, um deles perguntou o meu nome completo. Para minha surpresa e todos demais, ele exclamou: "You Abud? Me Abud! "

Permitam-me apresentar-lhes Abdel Majid Abud, meu primo perdido há muito tempo ...:)

Name: Lindsay_NYC
Title: [ 16 ] shooting up close and personal
Description:
Tripoli, Lebanon.

I had SO many photos from today that it was hard to choose just on to represent it in my YIP. I chose this one because it gives you a little bit of the feel of Tripoli but mostly because it shows how much we were shooting people today. I really like that aspect of street photography and no one in this group was shy to walk up to a complete stranger and take their picture. It helped that the people of Tripoli were so open to having their pictures taken and would stand totally natural while six people took their picture at the same time. I only saw a handful of people refuse to have their picture taken today.

Name: Bernardo Ricci Armani PhotographingAround.Me
Title: Tripoli - The Soap Maker
Description:
Tripoli is the largest city in northern Lebanon and the second-largest city in Lebanon. Situated 85 km north of the capital Beirut. In ancient times, it was the center of a Phoenician confederation which included Tyre, Sidon and Arados, hence the name Tripoli, meaning "triple city" in Greek. 

At the end of the 15th century, the governor of Tripoli (Lebanon) Youssef Bek Sayfa established Khan Al Saboun (the hotel of soap traders). This market was finished at the beginning of the 16th century, the last days of the Mamlouks ruling. The manufacture of soap was very popular in Tripoli. There, the market became a trade center where soap was produced and sold. Afterwards, traders of Tripoli began to export their soap to Europe.

At first, those perfumed soaps were offered as gifts in Europe. Therefore, handiwork developed in Tripoli. Due to the ongoing increase of the demand, craftsmen started to consider this job as a real art and wanted to satisfy their product amateurs by manufacturing various forms of more effective good-quality soap. That’s how the Arab and occidental countries began to import the soap of Tripoli. 

Nowadays, we find all kinds of soaps in Tripoli: slimming soaps, anti-acne soaps, moisturizing soaps… Some producers are even turning to exportation more than ever. The raw material used for these kinds of soap is olive oil. The Tripoli soap is also composed of: honey, essential oils, natural aromatic raw materials like: flowers, petals, herbs… The soaps are dried in the sun, in a dry atmosphere: this allows the evaporation of water that served to mix the different ingredients.
The drying operation lasts for almost three months. As water evaporates, a thin white layer appears on the soap surface: it is the soda that comes from the sea salts. 

The craftsman brushes the soap very carefully with his hand until the powder trace is entirely eliminated.

Title: Najib Coutya & Cahit Baylav (2011) 01
Description:
18th March 2011 at SOAS (JCR), London WC1.

"Songs of Sheikh Imam".

Country: Lebanon & Turkey (both British resident). Style: Egyptian Contemporary Song.

Lineup: Najib Coutya (v/oud), Cahit Baylav (violin)

Najib Coutya was born in Tripoli, Lebanon, moving to London in 1991. Cahit Baylav is from Ermenek, Turkey and came to the UK in 1982 (after an earlier spell as a postgraduate student). Sheikh Iman (Imam Mohammad Ahmad Eissa) was an Egyptian composer and singer (who died in 1995) known for his political songs supporting the poor.

Title: Tripoli old city  Sahat at-Tall  and the clock tower .

In 1901, a high tower with a large clock was built  to celebrate the  anniversary of Sultan 'Abd al-Hamid II's ascension to the throne.This clocktower is one of three similar clocks set into high towers in Beirut, (the most famous built a place d'Etoile in 1897)  and Haifa .Located in the heart of downtown Tripoli,the main gate for the old city, and is the transportation center and terminus for most taxi routes, (buses, mostly Mitsubishi Rosa and Nissan C), and what you wish for everywhere. with many plainclothes policemen, many political activists Anonymous, ready to......
i never see togheter a lot of mercedes 200 taxi like here in "at-Tall"!   ( Ponton series, circular,vertical rectangular, horizontal rectangular  lights series, and E series). more units are in very excellent condition, but a lot have poor body.
 lebanon  taxidriver  icon  with your  mercedes 200 said "The bizarre traffic conditions in  Tripoli( and ...) made "predictable driving" a phrase for comedians".  The red license plates are typical for taxis.

I instantly regretted not getting closer to these guys when I took this shot. But after seeing the final product, I guess I can live with it. You see more of the context, with the old arches, tattered A/C units, tacky string lights, and other real-life details. Still, I think this capture has a lonely solitary feel which is a little disingenuous -- it was actually a fairly lively corner.

Name: Meena Shah
Title: Camille Zakharia, 'Markings II'
Description:
Resisting:

Camille Zakharia
Born Tripoli, Lebanon, 1962. Lives Manama, Bahrain
'Markings II'
2008
Inkjet print on rag paper
Museum no. E.671-2011

Using photography, photomontage, collage, painting and print, Camille Zakharia makes work about identity and displacement, reflecting his own life journey and his interest as a trained engineer in architecture and the urban landscape.

In this work Zakharia digitally manipulates his source material until it is nearly illegible. He creates an abstract geometric form that is reminiscent of the patterns on Islamic tiles. The shape was made by repeating and rotating a photograph of a line of paint on asphalt. He explains, 'Through the use of montage, I have rebelled against the photo medium itself, challenging its reputation to represent reality as it is. I have liberated myself from the traditional photo process.'

Description:
Facing Storms With Cardboard

Zak Brophy

Tripoli, Lebanon, Jan 15 (IPS) - Zuhur al-Khalaf is eight months pregnant and lives in a one-room shack in northern Lebanon with her husband and five children. The cloth walls and cardboard roof have become sodden and musty after heavy storms this past week, and two of the children are suffering from fevers and chest infections.

Name: Maurelly
Title: Tripoli - Château Saint-Gilles
Description: Bâtie sur l'emplacement d'un fort construit par le commandant arabe Sufyan ibn Mujib al-Azdi en 636, le château Saint-Gilles (qalaat sanjil) ou Mont-Pèlerin a été étendu par Raymond IV de Saint-Gilles (1041-1105), Comte de Toulouse, en 1100 lors du siège de Tripoli. Incendié une première fois en 1287 et détruit par les mamelouks en 1289, reconstruit par l'émir Esendémir Kurdji en 1307, rénové par Soliman le Magnifique, et très largement remanié par le wali de Tripoli Mustapha Barbar Agha au début du XIXe pour servir de prison.

Name: egisto.sani
Title: Monumental Sarcophagus
Description:
The main side of this richly decorated monumental sarcophagus depicts the myth of Hippolytus and Phaedra. The myth’s iconography is well known. The young man is carved standing exactly in the center of the composition. He is about to leave for hunting and his horse is near him. Phaedra is sitting on a chair. She wears a short-sleeved chiton and a himation risen on her head and covering her legs . The queen is pining away for his son-in-law. She turns her head to the left towards a servant who, leaning toward her and taking her right arm with a familiar gesture, whispers in her ear words of hope or consolation. An Erote symbolizes the love of Phaedra for Hippolytus.
The old nurse of Phaedra stops the young hunter and gives him the tablets containing the love letter written by the queen. Phaedra doesn’t look towards him while the old nurse gives the fatal letter to Hippolytus. A hunting scene is carved in the right corner of the scene.
The sculptor has given to the naked Hippolytus the features of Antinous. A klamis wrapping around the left forearm is thrown over the left shoulder. The left hand holds a spear leaning on the shoulder; the sword attached to a harness going over the right shoulder is hanging on the left side. The right hand, placed at waist height, holds the tablets delivered to him by the nurse. But Hippolytus does not read the message: he turns left towards the old woman depicted by means of singularly individual features. She is looking and speaking towards Hippolytus; her words are accompanied with the gesture of her raised left hand.
The decorations of the friezes, of the lid, of the architectural elements of the sarcophagus are astonishingly rich.

Source: Catalogue Mendel, Tome 1, page 109, Notice 0026

Roman sarcophagus
2nd Century AD
From Tripoli, Lebanon
Istanbul, Archaeological Museum

Name: Thomas Rossi Rassloff
Title: Tripoli Refugee Camp img_0350_result
Description:
Lebanon Tripoli  19.10.2013
Flüchtlingslager / Refugee Camp

Exterior view of a Syrian refugee camp in Tripoli, Lebanon. Thousands have been displaced through the civil war in their home country.

Nach einer ereignisreichen Nacht im Hotel wandelte ich noch etwas verpennt zum Frühstücksbuffet. Die Auswahl war nicht riesig, aber zufrieden stellend. Schnell ein paar Bissen mit O-Saft runter gespült und raus. Vorm Hotel wartete schon das Auto mit meinem Fixer-Pärchen. Die Freundlichkeit der beiden trotz der Frühe des Tages ließen mich die Scheißnacht im Hotel schnell vergessen. 

Wir machten uns auf den Weg nach Tripoli, wo es Flüchtlingscamps geben soll. Auf den Weg besorgten wir noch Kaffee und etwas zu Essen. 
Tripoli bietet im Gegensatz zu Beirut eine ganz andere Stadtansicht. 
Beirut scheint das Zentrum des Wachstums im Libanon zu sein. Überall stehen Neubauten. Die Spuren des 25-jährigen Bürgerkriegs, der in den 90ern endete, sieht man nur noch versteckt hier und da an manchen Ecken. Zwar ist das libanesische Militär allgegenwärtig, aber die Checkpoints wirken gelangweilt und machen auf mich keinen negativen Eindruck. 
Ganz anders ist es in Tripoli: Die Stadt sieht so aus, als wäre der Krieg gerade erst zu Ende gegangen oder würde noch weiter stattfinden- was wohl genauer betrachtet eigentlich auch so ist. Denn im Zentrum von Tripoli befindet sich ein kleines Schiiten-Viertel inmitten einer sunnitisch geprägten Stadt. Mein Fixer meint dazu: „Tripoli sieht nicht nur syrisch aus, die Leute hier denken auch syrisch.“ Das Militär zeigt überall Präsenz, kann aber nicht verhindern, dass es hin und wieder Schießereien zwischen den sunnitischen und dem schiitischen Viertel kommt. Dass die verschiedenen Milizen selber Checkpoints einrichten, um Ihre Viertel vor Übergriffen zu schützen, lässt sich ebenfalls nicht verhindern. 

Schließlich erreichen wir das syrische Flüchtlingscamp  (Tanak Camp). Es liegt zwischen dem Mittelmeerstrand und der Stadt etwas versteckt hinter Sanddünen und Schilffeldern. Wenn es nicht gerade wie aus Eimern geschüttet hätte und die Wege nicht schlammig wären, könnte man das Hüttendorf fast romantisch finden, erinnert es an ein Hippiedorf auf einer der Kanarischen Inseln oder in der Karibik. Aber wir sind im Libanon. Es ist kühl, man versinkt im Schlamm und es kommt keine Urlaubsstimmung auf. Wir treffen ein paar Leute, die uns erklären,  dass ein paar von den Hütten schon lange vor dem syrischen Bürgerkrieg errichtet wurden, von Gastarbeitern bzw. Saisonarbeitern aus Syrien, die aus wirtschaftlichen Gründen im Libanon gestrandet waren. Aber seit ca. einem Jahr ist die kleine Notunterkunft zu einem mittelgroßen Camp angewachsen. 
Wir gehen weiter und treffen auf Fatima. Sie ist eine Art „Chefin“ bzw. Managerin des Camps, sie organisiert, sie plant und ist Ansprechpartnerin für Gäste und Leute wie mich, die ein paar Fragen haben. Fatima ist 32 und aus der Stadt Homs. Mit ihren drei Kinder und zwei jüngeren Schwestern (16 und 21) lebt sie im Camp. Als Fatimas Mann und ihr Schwager vom Regime ermordet wurden floh sie mit ihren Kindern und ihren Schwestern und strandete hier im wahrsten Sinne des Wortes. Nun hoffen sie auf Hilfe von außen und versuchen ihren Alltag so gut es geht zu managen. Ihre jüngste Tochter trägt einen Namen Mashael bzw. Mashal, der die Fackel (der Freiheit) bedeutet. Sie ist ungefähr 9 Jahre alt und blüht vor Lebensenergie. Fatima erzählt die letzte Anekdote ihrer Tochter so: „Meine Tochter spielte am Strand und sah Touristen in Badekleidung am Strand liegen. Am nächsten Tag legte sie sich auch 'nur' in Unterwäsche zum Sonnen an den Strand. Auf ihre Freizügigkeit angesprochen entgegnet sie, dass wir doch jetzt in Freiheit leben!“ 
Homs gilt nach wie vor als eine sehr konservative, sunnitische Stadt. Hier tragen die Frauen lange Kleidung und Schleier. Haut zu zeigen ist unerwünscht. 

Wir trinken weiter Tee und reden etwas über Politik, vom Westen, der zu wenig hilft, das überhaupt zu wenig bei den Leuten ankommt, das Übliche - leider. 


Dann machen wir uns wieder auf den Weg ins Koora Camp, fast um die Ecke. Hier ist ein Verwandter von Fatima mit seiner Familie unter gekommen. Ihr Sohn soll uns begleiten und den Weg zeigen und vor Ort etwas behilflich sein. Nach 10 Minuten mit dem Auto sind wir da. Das Camp liegt in einer Olivenplantage auf privatem Besitz und besteht aus ca. 20 Hütten, die aus Blech, Holz und Plane zusammen geflickt wurden. Auch hier ist der Boden vom Regen verschlammt und es fällt schwer einen festen und sicheren Halt beim Gehen zu finden. Manche Wege sind mit Geröll ausgelegt. Zumindest dort steht man etwas sicherer. Als wir beim Gemeinschaftszelt  ankommen, werden wir von Anwohnern umringt. Es wird laut diskutiert. Ich verstehe nicht all zu viel. Muschkila - Problem, keine Fotos. OK. Die Campbewohner sind sichtlich genervt von ihren Lebensumständen und pappensatt von Leuten, die kommen, um Fotos zu machen, Gespräche zu führen, Versprechungen zu machen und dann wieder verschwinden und nie wieder auftauchen. 
Ich verstehe das. Wir einigen uns darauf, dass ich keine Fotos innerhalb des Camps mache und nur von außen fotografiere. Gesagt getan. 
Wir fahren zurück nach Beirut.

Title: #FBT
Description:
#FBT In the beginning of the 14th AC, Khan Al Saboun was the first trade center in the Middle East area and has acquired a prestigious post in the international trade world for specializing in natural cosmetics and handmade soaps. 
 The inheriting family led by Dr. Bader Hassoun of Tripoli, Lebanon, practiced the science of pharmacy & natural therapy from more than 600 years ago and has revived the Khan Al Saboun legend till today by developing a special line of beauty and cosmetics as natural skincare. addition to organic food production like olive oil ,rose water blossom water and all this in the environmental village of Dr. Bader Hassoun

Name: Reportages ici et ailleurs
Title: IMG_3318.jpg
Description: Beddawi camp, Tripoli, Lebanon. Le conflit syrien est très présent dans les camps libanais. Certains partis palestiniens, le fatah-intifada où le pflp-gc sont ouvertement pro-gouvernement, alors que la majorité des autres partis préfère garder une position de neutralité. Même si nombre de personnes, y compris des palestiniens de Syrie, gardent des affinités avec le gouvernement syrien pour son soutien, réel ou supposé, à la cause palestinienne.
